People who didn't use a computer in like 2006 have zero memory how glitchy everything was. Like your PC used to just randomly freeze and crash browsing the internet. Windows OS bugs out and you have to reinstall everything. Everything constantly crashing and freezing. BSOD daily.

Maybe I just had the most ghetto Bulgarian 90s setup of all time but I remember constantly just having everything crash to the point it was unusable some days. Computer viruses were a real thing and could physically fry your hardware.

I sort of find the twitter porno bots nostalgic because adblock was also not yet a thing and regular websites had porno ads and graphic dick pill ads were everywhere so you just scrolled or played browser games etc. with them on the sides. Most ppl probably no longer remember it.

Basically picking one lift and doing it every single day for 1-2 weeks trying to hit a one rep max PR every day until you plateau. Very low volume, no hyperventilating, actually very fun. You have to watch his old vids to get it. Not for everyone (me included) but it's very sound

I feel like the internet has culturally shamed "nice guys" way too much making fun of phrases like "nice guys finish last" etc. when this type of very well-mannered and decent guy exists in reality and always makes a wonderful friend (or a boyfriend and husband, from observation)

Has to do with the "guy who has lots of stories of driving women at night and picking them from the airport" archetype, but this type of guy naturally is very reserved, distant, tactful, never makes the first move etc. so it's cruel to culturally push him to act so unlike himself

Basically everyone should respect the type of guy who is not an "alpha male", but still comports himself with dignity, modesty, speaks softly and politely, knows how to always collect himself and is private, beyond trustworthy, etc. Dignity deserves to be admired and appreciated.
Well I still would because it often leads to failure and bitterness but on the larger societal scale it should be appreciated
